{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627216"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:46:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:46:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17109"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17109","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17109"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.56,0.23,0.1,0.06,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9799"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77019"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9799"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17109"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62525"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5054"},{"type":"tags","id":"10069"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22977"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23114"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77019","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77019"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman with hypercholesterolaemia is reviewed by her general practitioner. Despite treatment with atorvastatin, her low-density lipoprotein cholesterol remains elevated. Her doctor decides to add ezetimibe to her treatment regimen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of ezetimibe?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibits intestinal cholesterol absorption protein","Increases low-density lipoprotein receptor expression","Inhibits cholesterol synthesis in the liver","Increases bile acid excretion","Reduces triglyceride synthesis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EEzetimibe works by \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibiting intestinal cholesterol absorption protein\u003C/strong\u003E (specifically the Niemann-Pick C1-Like 1 protein) in the brush border of small intestinal cells. This reduces the absorption of both dietary and biliary cholesterol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other mechanisms are incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases low-density lipoprotein receptor expression\u003C/strong\u003E may occur as an indirect effect, but it is not the primary mechanism through which ezetimibe lowers cholesterol levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits cholesterol synthesis in the liver\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of action of statins, which work by inhibiting the enzyme HMG-CoA reductase.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases bile acid excretion\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of action of bile acid sequestrants such as cholestyramine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduces triglyceride synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect; ezetimibe does not have a direct effect on triglyceride metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy reducing cholesterol absorption in the intestine, ezetimibe leads to lower blood cholesterol levels. It is particularly effective when combined with statins, as it provides a complementary mechanism of action.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Ezetimibe reduces cholesterol absorption by inhibiting the Niemann-Pick C1-Like 1 protein in intestinal cells.","Ezetimibe acts specifically in the small intestine to reduce dietary and biliary cholesterol absorption.","Ezetimibe can be used alone or in combination with statins to lower blood cholesterol levels."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62525"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17109"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62525","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62525"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T22:31:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T22:32:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9799"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77019"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"